05671nam a22009135i 9780231510684DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2007    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315106847 a10.7312/aydi137782doi  a(DE-B1597)458620  a(OCoLC)1013966069  a(OCoLC)1029834533  a(OCoLC)1032695301  a(OCoLC)1037973559  a(OCoLC)1041981720  a(OCoLC)1046606771  a(OCoLC)1046998056  a(OCoLC)1049659468  a(OCoLC)1054877476  a(OCoLC)979739418  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDS35.7b.A95 2007eb 7aHIS0030002bisacsh04a303.48/21767018212221 aAydin, Cemil, eauthor.14aThe Politics of Anti-Westernism in Asia :bVisions of World Order in Pan-Islamic and Pan-Asian Thought /cCemil Aydin. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Studies in International and Global History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction -- t2. The Universal West -- t3. The Two Faces of the West -- t4. The Global Moment of the Russo-Japanese War -- t5. The Impact of WWI on Pan-Islamic and Pan-Asianist Visions of World Order -- t6. The Triumph of Nationalism? -- t7. The Revival of a Pan-Asianist Vision of World Order in Japan (1931-1945) -- t8. Conclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this rich intellectual history, Cemil Aydin challenges the notion that anti-Westernism in the Muslim world is a political and religious reaction to the liberal and democratic values of the West. Nor is anti-Westernism a natural response to Western imperialism. Instead, by focusing on the agency and achievements of non-Western intellectuals, Aydin demonstrates that modern anti-Western discourse grew out of the legitimacy crisis of a single, Eurocentric global polity in the age of high imperialism.Aydin compares Ottoman Pan-Islamic and Japanese Pan-Asian visions of world order from the middle of the nineteenth century to the end of World War II. He looks at when the idea of a universal "West" first took root in the minds of Asian intellectuals and reformers and how it became essential in criticizing the West for violating its own "standards of civilization." Aydin also illustrates why these anti-Western visions contributed to the decolonization process and considers their influence on the international relations of both the Ottoman and Japanese Empires during WWI and WWII. The Politics of Anti-Westernism in Asia offers a rare, global perspective on how religious tradition and the experience of European colonialism interacted with Muslim and non-Muslim discontent with globalization, the international order, and modernization. Aydin's approach reveals the epistemological limitations of Orientalist knowledge categories, especially the idea of Eastern and Western civilizations, and the way in which these limitations have shaped not only the contradictions and political complicities of anti-Western discourses but also contemporary interpretations of anti-Western trends. In moving beyond essentialist readings of this history, Aydin provides a fresh understanding of the history of contemporary anti-Americanism as well as the ongoing struggle to establish a legitimate and inclusive international society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aInternational cooperation. 0aPanislamism. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z97